- VSCode Version: Version 1.15.1 (1.15.1)
- OS Version: OSX 10.11.6

Steps to Reproduce:

1. The minimal sample codes:
```ts
interface Component<P, S> {
  componentWillMount?(): void;
  componentDidMount?(): void;
  componentWillReceiveProps?(nextProps: Readonly<P>, nextContext: any): void;
  shouldComponentUpdate?(nextProps: Readonly<P>, nextState: Readonly<S>, nextContext: any): boolean;
  componentWillUpdate?(nextProps: Readonly<P>, nextState: Readonly<S>, nextContext: any): void;
  componentDidUpdate?(prevProps: Readonly<P>, prevState: Readonly<S>, prevContext: any): void;
  componentWillUnmount?(): void;
}
class Component<P, S> {
}

class MyComponent extends Component<{}, {}> {
  // Mark1
  shouldComponentUpdate(nextProps, nextState, nextContext) {}
  // Mark2
}
```
2. Two problems:

    a. [maybe bug] At Mark1 and Mark 2, typing ctrl + space gives me intelligence suggestion: all the life cycle methods. MyComponent just extends the Component not implements it. Compare with typescript playground, I can't even get any suggestions in `extends` or `implements` way. Does it is a bug that we get suggestions?

    b. Assuming point a is normal behavior. 
        [bug] At Mark1, after popping suggested methods and select, auto-completion provides us the full method skeleton. e.g. type character 'c' (or ctrl + space), then select the `componentDidUpdate`, auto-completion produces 'componentDidUpdate(prevProps, prevState, prevContext)'.
        [bug] At Mark2, type character 'c', I can't get any methods suggestion.
        [bug] At Mark2, type ctrl + space, I get the unused methods suggestion. If I select one, auto-completion only produces the method's name. e.g. 'componentWillReceiveProps'. I have to fill the parameters, compare with Mark1 the different behavior make me confused.

<!-- Launch with `code --disable-extensions` to check. -->
Reproduces without extensions: Yes
